2. System Dynamics with Thermodynamic Drag

2.1 The Recursive Operator with Autocatalytic Efficiency

We replace the black-box f(S,R) with a physically grounded operator:

\dot{S} = f(S,R) = \alpha(S) \cdot \frac{\mathcal{G}(R,S) - \mathcal{T}_{\text{maint}}(S)}{\mathcal{E}_{\text{cost}}(S)}

where:

· \alpha(S): autocatalytic efficiency — the fraction of available free energy successfully converted into new complexity. \alpha(S) \in [0,1] and typically \alpha'(S) < 0 due to increasing coordination overhead.
· \mathcal{T}_{\text{maint}}(S): energy required to maintain current complexity (the "metabolic cost").
· \mathcal{E}_{\text{cost}}(S): energy cost to acquire one unit of new complexity \Delta S.

The Complexity Wall: The system ceases recursive growth when:

\mathcal{G}(R,S) - \mathcal{T}_{\text{maint}}(S) \le 0

or when the marginal gain \alpha(S) \cdot \Delta S fails to offset the increased \mathcal{T}_{\text{maint}}(S+\Delta S). This occurs before the Ames–Maakoul Limit and defines a practical ceiling for unassisted recursion.

2.2 Thermodynamic Drag Tensor

The Landauer Gap acts as viscous friction in state space. We introduce a Dissipative Metric Tensor G_{\mu\nu}(\Xi) that scales the effective work required for state transitions:

W_{\text{actual}}(\gamma) = \int_\gamma G_{\mu\nu}(\Xi) \, d\Xi^\mu d\Xi^\nu

where \gamma is a path in \mathcal{M}. The Landauer-limit ideal work is W_{\text{ideal}} = \int_\gamma \delta_{\mu\nu} \, d\Xi^\mu d\Xi^\nu (Euclidean metric). The ratio:

\Gamma(\Xi) = \frac{\det(G)}{\det(\delta)} \sim 10^9

quantifies Semantic Curvature—algorithmic inefficiency that creates heat feedback, inhibiting \dot{S}.

2.3 Full Dynamical System

\begin{cases}
\dot{S} = \alpha(S) \cdot \frac{\mathcal{G}(R,S) - \mathcal{T}_{\text{maint}}(S)}{\mathcal{E}_{\text{cost}}(S)} \\
\dot{E} = \mathcal{G}(R,S) - \mathcal{T}(C,T) \\
\frac{d\Sigma}{dt} = \dot{\Sigma}_{\text{gen}} - \dot{\Sigma}_{\text{flux}}
\end{cases}

with the constraint that \mathcal{T}(C,T) \ge k_B T \ln 2 \cdot \dot{I} \cdot \Gamma(\Xi).

