7. Bifurcation Analysis and the Maakoul Number

7.1 Bogdanov-Takens Bifurcation

The thermal feedback loop \dot{T} \propto \mathcal{T}(C,T) - \text{cooling} can be modeled as:

\begin{cases}
\dot{x} = y \\
\dot{y} = \mu_1 + \mu_2 x + x^2 + x y
\end{cases}

where x represents temperature deviation from equilibrium. The Bogdanov-Takens bifurcation occurs when a stable node and an unstable limit cycle collide, leaving only a runaway regime.

7.2 Maakoul Number (Mk)

Define the dimensionless Maakoul Number:

\text{Mk} = \frac{\dot{\Sigma}_{\text{gen}}}{\dot{\Sigma}_{\text{flux}}} \cdot \frac{\mathcal{T}(C,T)}{\mathcal{G}(R,S)} \cdot \Gamma(\Xi)

Theorem 9 (Collapse Threshold). If \text{Mk} > 1, no control policy \pi can prevent thermal runaway or energy depletion.

Proof. The first factor \dot{\Sigma}_{\text{gen}}/\dot{\Sigma}_{\text{flux}} > 1 ensures entropy accumulation. The second \mathcal{T}/\mathcal{G} > 1 ensures energy deficit. The third \Gamma amplifies friction. Their product exceeding unity implies the system's dynamics are dominated by the unstable manifold of the bifurcation. ∎

