9. SRI Scaling Law (Kleiber's Analogue)

9.1 Proposed Scaling Law

\mathcal{G}(R,S) \propto S^\beta

where \beta is the scaling exponent.

9.2 Criticality of \beta

· If \beta < 1: Sublinear — larger systems are more efficient per unit complexity. SRI is scalable.
· If \beta = 1: Linear — neutral scaling.
· If \beta > 1: Superlinear — infrastructure must grow faster than complexity. This implies a hard thermodynamic ceiling for unassisted recursive AGI.

Empirical data from data center scaling suggests \beta \approx 1.2–1.4 for current architectures, indicating that recursive AGI without fundamental thermodynamic innovation is inherently unstable at large scales.

