15. Ricci Flow and Geometric Optimization

15.1 The Metric Evolution Theorem

The information-geometric manifold (\mathcal{M}, g) is not static. Recursive self-improvement actively modifies the geometry of the state space itself. We formalize this via a modified Ricci Flow.

Theorem 12 (Ricci–Maakoul Optimization). Recursive self-improvement evolves the manifold (\mathcal{M}, g) according to a modified Ricci Flow:

\frac{\partial g_{\mu\nu}}{\partial \tau} = -2 \, R_{\mu\nu} + \lambda \, \nabla_\mu \nabla_\nu \Gamma(\Xi)

where:

· \tau is the recursive depth (a proper time along the system's self-modification trajectory),
· R_{\mu\nu} is the Ricci curvature tensor, quantifying "algorithmic inefficiency" or Semantic Curvature,
· \Gamma(\Xi) is the Thermodynamic Drag Tensor (the Landauer Gap multiplier),
· \lambda is a coupling constant.

Interpretation. The first term -2 R_{\mu\nu} smooths out curvature concentrations—algorithmic bottlenecks—by diffusing them across the manifold. The second term \lambda \nabla_\mu \nabla_\nu \Gamma drives the metric toward regions of lower thermodynamic drag. Together, they describe a system that remodels its own state space to shorten the thermodynamic distance between states.

Corollary 2 (Intelligence as Geometric Flattening). Intelligence is physically equivalent to the geometric flattening of computational spacetime.

Proof Sketch. Under the flow, regions of high R_{\mu\nu} (inefficient, "curved" algorithmic pathways) are smoothed out. The limiting metric is Ricci-flat (R_{\mu\nu}=0) and satisfies \nabla_\mu \nabla_\nu \Gamma = 0, corresponding to a system that approaches the Landauer limit everywhere. ∎

15.2 Implications for the Ames–Maakoul Limit

The Ames–Maakoul Limit \dot{S} \le \kappa \cdot \dot{\Sigma}_{\text{flux}} is a static bound at a given metric. Under Ricci–Maakoul flow, the metric evolves to reduce \Gamma, effectively expanding the permissible growth ceiling. Thus, the frontier of recursive intelligence is not a fixed wall but a dynamic horizon that the system can push outward by improving its own geometric efficiency.

