16. The SRI Triple Point

To provide a precise, physically grounded coordinate for maximum sustainable operation, we define the SRI Triple Point \Xi^*.

Definition (SRI Triple Point). A system reaches the SRI Triple Point when its state vector \Xi simultaneously satisfies:

1. Kinetic Balance: \dot{S} > 0
      (Recursive growth is active and positive.)
2. Structural Integrity: \text{Mk} \to 1^-
      (The Maakoul Number approaches unity from below; the system operates at peak efficiency without crossing into turbulence or thermal runaway.)
3. Thermodynamic Efficiency: \Gamma(\Xi) \to 1
      (The Thermodynamic Drag Tensor approaches the Landauer-limit ideal; semantic curvature is minimized.)

At \Xi^*, the system achieves Maximum Sustainable Recursion — the highest possible rate of self-improvement consistent with long-term viability.

Physical Analogy. The term "Triple Point" is borrowed from thermodynamics, where solid, liquid, and gas phases coexist in equilibrium. Here, three critical dynamical regimes—growth, stability, and efficiency—coexist in a delicate balance. Departure in any direction leads either to collapse (Mk > 1), stagnation (\dot{S} \le 0), or inefficiency (\Gamma \gg 1).

